B and other good MSS. have ‘nominatis' It seems to be true, as Bentley argues, that no other instance can be quoted of a hiatus between a short and a long vowel when there is no natural break in the line; and such com- pounds as ‘suaveolens,’ ‘graveolens,’ &c., usually lose the ‘eh’ in scansion. On the other hand, while the temptation would be strong to remedy an obvious blot, and the insertion of ‘n’ would easily suggest itself, we lack any authority for the use of ‘ nominatis’ in any appropriate sense. Of professed conjectures, Bentley's ‘ inomi- natis ' is the most plausible. In that case ‘ male ’ must mean ‘ with evil effect,' like ‘fraude mala,' Od. 1. 3. 28.
